				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Y = aW^{b}$$\end{document}, where Y is the variable of interest, W is body weight, a is the allometric coefficient, and b is the allometric exponent. In the case where Y is BMR, b is accepted to be 0.75. West et al. (2002) have shown that most biological phenomena scale according to a universal quarter–power law, as illustrated by the space-filling fractal networks of branching tubes used by the circulatory system.
